{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_inman_ver01/data/sn85038485/0034058367A/1913061801/0985.xml":{"full_text":"THE BIRMINGHAM AGE HERALD\nVOLUME XXXXIII _ BIRMINGHAM, ALABAMA, WEDNESDAY, JUNE 18, 1913 SECTION G NUMBER 43\nEARLY ALABAMA HISTORY\nAND BIOGRAPHICAL DATA\nA Vital, Thrilling and Interesting Record of More Than Three\nHundred and Eighty Years\nBy THOMAS M. OWE A', LL. D.\nDirector of the Alabama State Department of Archives and History, and a\na native of Jefferson County.\nAlthough other local areas have had a\nlonger organized existence, either as col\nonies or provinces, and states, no part of\nthe American union is to be found with a\nmore ptcturesque and instructive record\nthan tho more than 52,000 square miles\nembraced within the limits of the present\nstate of Alabama. And, however fasci\nnating Its colonial annals, none the less\ncompelling in appeal Is the record of\nstatehood and the many vital problems\ndeveloped in the ongoing of the life of\nthe people.\nA brief recital here will serve to Justify\nand at the same time to touch the pride\nof all patriotic Alabamians.\nChronological Outline\nFrom its first exploration in the early\nyears of tho sixteenth century the terri\ntory embraced in the state of Alabama\nhas a thrilling history.\nWithin 50 years after the discovery of\nAmerica, or In 1540, De Soto, with his iron-\nclad warriors and white-stoled priests,\npassed like an angry meteor through its\nborders. On October 18 bf thut year he\nfought the great battle of Mauvilla, the\nmost sanguinary of Indian conflicts on\ntho American continent.\nThe earliest permanent settlement in the\ngulf states was founded in January, 1702,\nat T wenty-seven Mile Rluff, Mobile river,\nknown as Fort Louis, tne site of old Mo\nbile. Removed to its present location In\n3711, this city was until 1720 the capital ol\\\nthe province of Louisiana.\nIn 3714 Fort ToulouHe, near the conflu\nence of the Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers,\nwas planted as a remote outpost for In\ndian trade and as a buffer to the English\nadvance from the South Atlantic sea\nboard. In 1912 the Colonial Dames of Ala\nbama dedicated a memorial shaft on its\nsite. In 1721 tho first African slaves were\nlanded at Mobile.\nOn February 18, 1753. France ceded all\nher possessions east of the Mississippi\nriver, excepting the Island of Orleans, to\nGreat Britain.\nBy treaty of November 30, 1782, marking\nthe close of the contest of the colonics\nwith the mother country, Great Britain\nceded to them all of her possessions north\nof latitude 31 degrees,, and on October 27,\n1793, Spain relinquished to the United\nStates her claims to West Florida, south\nof line 31 degrees.\nTho Mississippi Territory was formed\nby act of Congress, April 7. 1798, and un\nder this and subsequent ucts all of the\npresent states of Mississippi and Alabama\ncomprised one territory until 1817.\nOn March 3, 1817, Alubama Territory\nFRANK N. JULIAN\nAssociate Railroad Commissioner of\nAlabama\n\u2014Photo by Stephenson\nMr. Julian has been a member of the\nstate railroad commission since 1911. and\nduring his Incumbency of the office has\nmade a most enviable reputation.\nThrough his efforts many needed im\nprovements have been secured and in the\ndischarge of his official duties Mr.\nJulian has visited every county In the\nMatei In the next primary election Mr.\nJulian \u25a0will ask for re-election, basing his\nclaims upon the party precedent of a sec\nond term and upon the record he lias\nmade of faithful performance of the\nduties of the joffiee.\nwas former], and after the adoption of a\nconstitution under an enabling act of\nMarch 2, 1819, on December 14 following,\nthe state was admitted into the federal\nunion.\nThe temporary seat of 'government of\nthe Alabama Territory was at Old St.\nStephens, on the Tombigbee river. In\n1818 Cahaba was selected as the capital;\nin 1826 it was removed to Tuscaloosa, and\nin 1846 to Montgomery.\nThe state seceded from the federal un\nion January 11,1861, and February 4, 1861,\nunited in the formation of the provisional\ngovernment of the Confederate States of\nAmerica.\nOn June 21, 1865. Bewis E. Parsons was\nappointed provisional governor.\nOn November 24. 1874, George S. Hous\nton wus inaugurated governor. With his\ninauguration negro and carpetbag rule\nended.\nSix constitutional conventions have as\nsembled in the state, making and amend\ning tlie organic law, namely, 1819, 1861,\n1865, 1867, 1877 and 1901.\nSignificent and Conspicuous Facts\nWithin the limits of the state dwelt for\nhundreds of years the four great Indian\ntribes\u2014the Cherokees, the Creeks, the\nChoctaws and the Chiekasaws. Here were\nborn and reared McGillivray and Weath\nerford and Osceola and Stan Watie, and\nhero resided the Colberts, the Ridges,\nRoss, Sequoyah, McIntosh and others.\nAaron Burr, distinguished in the Revo\nlutionary war, and vice president of the\nUnited States, while a fugitive from the\ncourts, was captured in the AlabaVna sec\ntion of the Mississippi Territory.\nIn the campaigns against the Creek In\ndians in the var of 1813 and 1814 Andrew\nJackson entered upon that long public\ncareer so notable in American history.\nOf the several territories Alabama was\nsettled more rapidly and passed more\nquieky from territorial pupilage than any\nother.\nIn April, 1825, General BaFayette, on\nhis last tour through the United States,\npassed through Alabama.\nIn 1832 was completed the first railway\ntrack west of the Alleghany mountains,\nextending from Tuscumbta in the direc\ntion of Decatur, and now forming a part\nof the Southern railway system.\nAlabama was the first of the cotton\nstates to establish a. common school sys\ntem.\nCradle of Confederacy\nMontgomery, the state capital, was the\n\u201cCradle of the Confederacy.\u201d in the his\ntoric state capitol building, February 4,\nJ. LEE LONG,\nChairman of the State Tax Commission*\nDuring the past two months. Mr.\nLong has frequently been mentioned as\na candidate for gdvernor In the next\nDemocratic primary. Mr. Long Is one\nof the best known men In Alabama,\nhaving been twice elected a member\nof the legislature and having been Iden\ntified with various political movements\ntn the state during the past 10 years.\nHe made a vigorous fight against the\nAmendment to the Constitution pro\nviding for state-wide prohibition, and\nwas Governor O'Neal's campaign mas\nter in 1910.\nJOHN H. WALLACE, JR.\n\"By the grace of God and the help of the people of Alabama, I propose to\n\u2022trike vengeance from the criminal law of this state, and mako the sentence\nof the criminal one of correction and not of retaliation; I propose to build men,\n{to compel them to use tbe stepping atones of their dead selves to rise to\n\u25a0higher and nobler things.\"\ni\n1861, the delegates from six seceding\nstates met (in the senate chamber) and\norganized the provisional government of\nthe Confederate States of America. Here\nthey adopted a provisional constitution;\nhere they elected Jefferson Davis and\nAlexander Stephe'ns, President and vice\npresident, respectively, of the new con\nfederation, and here on the front portico\nMr. Davis was inaugurated in the pres\nence of applauding thousands on Feb\nruary 18, 1861.\nA formal proclamation of war was\nmade April lo. 1861, by Abraham Lincoln,\nPresident of the United States. At onco\nthe brave and patriotic people of Ala\nbama rallied to the defense of the state.\nThe .sentiment of the people is happily\ndescribed by Gov. Thomas H. Watts in\nhis inaugural address of December 1, 1863:\n\u2018\u2018And when the first tocsin of war\nsounded co-operationlsts and secessionists\nmarched shoulder to shoulder, heart to\nheart, hand to hand, to the arbitrament\nof battle. From the gulf to our northern\nborder, from the mountains, valleys and\nplains, from the east and from the west,\nthe stalwart sons of Alabama rushed to\nthe standard of the new-born republic,\nand with dauntless bravery and heroism\nthey have crimsoned with their blood\nevery battlefield from Manassas to Chiek\namauga. An imperishable monument of\nglorious renown has been erected for the\nstate. The name \u2018Alabamian' lias be\nj come immortal in our history.\u201d\nThe number of soldiers from Alabama\nwho enlisted during- the war was esti\nmated by Governor Parsons, in an offi\ncial proclamation of July, 1865, at 122,000,\nof a total white population of 526,271 In\nI860. Of these, he states, that at least\n35,000 are believed to have lost their lives,\nwhile a large number were permanently\ndisabled by wounds or disease. These\ntroops comprised, substantially three regi\nments and 13 companies, Alabama Volun\nteer Cforps, 1861; 60 regiments and 20 bat\ntalions of infantry; 14 regiments, 32 bat\ntalions and 39 independent companies of\ncavalry, four battalions and 20 batteries\nof artillery, 10 Confederate regiments and\none Confederate \u2019battalion, one or more\ncompanies in 14 commands from other\nstates, io reserve regiments and battal\nions, and in addition more than 100 local\ndefense organizations which saw active\nservice. There was no important battle\noast of the Mississippi river in which its\ntroops did not perform an honorable part,\nand some of the most brilliant general\nofficers were Alabamians, either by birth\nor by adoption.\nIn a report to Gov. I*ewis E. Parsons,\nDecember 4, 1865, Col. William H. Fowler,\nstate superintendent of army records,\nsays:\n\u201d1 assert with confidence that Alabama\nsent more troops into the service in pro\nportion to population than any other\nstate of the south, ami that her loss was\nheavier than any other, irrespective of\npopulation. I am certain, too, that when\nGeneral I*ee surrendered his army the\nrepresentation from Alabama on the field\nthat day was inferior to no other south\nern state in numbers, and surely not in\ngallantry;\nIn 1874 the state was redeemed from\nnegro and carpetbag rule, under the\nTeadershlp \u201ci5f Ge<7fge S. Houston,\nfrom that period to the present it has\nhad an almost phenomenal growth and\ndevelopment. In material advance 'that\nprogress has been unparalleled, as is ev\nidenced by the growth of mining, timber\nand manufacturing industries, the en\nlargement of shipping interests, the in\ncrease of railroad mileage, the improve\nment of the public roads and the found\ning of new towns. In agriculture there\nhas been utarked progress in scientific\nand progressive methods.\nIn Montgomery was built and operated\nIIRAXTON II. (OURR\n\u2014Photo by Stephenson\nEx-Governor R. R. Comer, one of the\nmost striking figures in Alabama's poli\ntics, is an announced candidate for re\nelection to that office. A successful busi\nness man and prominent church \u2019jvorker\nGovernor Comer entered the political field\nbut a few years ago. when he ran and\nwas elected president of the railroad\ncomfnlssion. He announced for governor\non a \u2018\u2018railroad rate reform\u201d platform and\nafter a spectacular campaign was elected\nby a Inge majority. He carried out his\nplatform promises add was the moving\nspirit in the legislation acts regulating\nthe railroads.\nWILLIAM F. FBAQIN\n\u2014Photo by Stephenson\nWilliam F. Feagrin. chief clerk in the\ndepartment of education, who will be\na candidate for state superintendent of\neducation in the next Democratic pri\nmary. Mr. Feasin will makChla formal\nannouncement later.\n;J-.~ -V f f .\u2018k. Y\ntile first electric railway In the l nited\nStates.\nThe state geological survey, created\nfirst in 1847. was revived in 1873, and under\nthe intelligent direction of Dr. Eugene A.\nSmith, state geologist, has opened to the\nworld the wonderful resources of the\nstate, and as an Institution has become a\nmodel for many of the new surveys.\nAt Auburn Prof. A. F. McKissick con\nstructed the first apparatus used in the\nt'nited States for the demonstration of\nthe X-ray.\nThe Alabama Polytechnic Institute at\nAuburn was the first southern college to\nestablish a separate chair of electrical\nengineering.\nThe establishment of the Alaliama state\ndepartment of archives and history hi\n1901 whs the first attempt in the l nited\nDR. THOMAS M. OWEN\nof Montgomery, director of the Ala\nbama State Department of Arch\nives and History.\n\nStates, through legislation, to meet the\nduty of the state to its archives (public\nrecords of every character) and history,\nthrough a separate department of govern\nment, administered by\u2018a state officer.\nA Few Distinguished Names\nAlabama has been the birthplace, or the i\ntemporary or permanent home, of many\ndistinguished men and women. Some of\nthem are:\nHenri de Tonty, explorer, buried at old\nFort Louis (first site of Mobile), on Twen\nty-seven Mile Bluff, Mobile river.\nBienville, the father of Louisiana.\nSir Robert Farmer, commandant of Mo\nbile.\nEphraim Kirby, appointed first judge In\nthe Alabama section (Washington dis\ntrict) of the Mississippi Territory, 1801,\ndied the same year, and is buried near\nthe present Mt. Vernon, Alabama river;\nhad served with credit in the Revolution\nary war; was the first general grand high\npriest of the Royal Arch Masons in the\nUnited States, and reported and published\nthe first volume (First Connecticut) of\ndecisions of any supreme court in the\nUnited States.\nHenry Toulmin, second territorial judge\n-of-Washington district, Mississippi Terri\ntory.\nCol. John Coffee, the right arm of Jack\nson in the Creek war, and first surveyor\nof public lands in the stuto.\nWilliam Rufus King, long a federal sen\nator and a vice president of the United\nStates.\nJohn McKinley, federal senator and\nmember of the United States supreme\ncourt.\nWilliam Lowndes Yancey, planter, edl\ntor, lawyer, member of the general aW\nsembly and state senate, member of Coi^\ngress, political leader, Confederate Statf\ncommissioner to Europe, and Confederate\nStates senator from Alabama.\nHenry Washington Hilliard, teacher,\nmember of Congress, preacher, diplomat,\ni orator and author.\nGen. Leroy Pope Walker, first Confed\nerate States secretary of war.\nCol. Thomas Hill Watts, Confederate\nStates attorney general and governor of\nAlabama.\nDavid Hubbard ami Col. Sutton S.\nScott, successive commissioners of Indian\naffairs. Confederate States of America.\nAdmiral Raphael Semmes, commander\nof the cruiser \"Alabama.\u201d Confederate\nStates navy.\nJohn Archibald Campbell, judge of the\nUnited States supreme court and assist\nant secretary of war. Confederate State*\nof America.\nDoctors Josiah C. Nott, ,7. Marion\nHIms. Nathan Bozeman. Paul H. Lewis,\nPeter Bryee, Jerome Cochran. John A.\nWyeth and William M. Polk, all Illus\ntrious physicians and surgeons.\nDr. J. L. M. Curry, member of Congress,\nj political leader and educator, and whose\ni effigy in marble is one of Alabama's rep\nresentatives in Statuary Hall, In the eap\nj itol at Washington.\nGen. James Longstreet and Gen. John\nB. Gordon were each carried on the rolls\nof the Confederacy accredited to Ala\nbama, although both directly after the\nwar moved to Georgia.\nDr. Lafayette Guild, medical director of\nthe Army of Northern Virginia.\nGen. John T. Morgan, federal senator\nand father of the interoceanic canal\nmovement.\nGen. Edmund W. Pettus, lawyer and\nfederal senator.\nGen. Joseph Wheeler, hero of two wars,\nand member of Congress.\nHon. Thomas G. Jones, governor and\nfederal district judge.\nHon. John H. Bankhead, father of the\ngood roads movement and promoter of\nriver and, harbor Improvement in Ala\nbama, representative In Congress and\nfederal senator.\nCol. Hilary A. Herbert, member of Con\ngress and member of President Cleve\nland\u2019s second cabinet as Secretary of\nthe Navy.\nHon. Joseph F. Johnston, governor and\nfederal senator.\nJudge Henderson M. Somerville, asso\nciate justice, supreme court of Alabama,\nand member United States board of cus\ntoms appraisers.\nDr. Hannls Taylor, author, lawyer and\npublicist.\nHon. Oscar W. LTnderwood, the. match\nless leader of the democracy and formid\nable candidate for the presidency In 1912.\nRichmond Pearson Hobson, \u201chero'* of\nthe Merrimac and representative In Con\ngress.\nReese Hutchinson, \u201celectrical wizard,\u2019\u2019\nand inventor of numerous electrical de\nvices.\nMrs. Caroline Lee Hentz, Madam Oe\ntavia Walton LeVert, Mrs. Augusta\nEvans Wilson, Mrs. Virginia Clay-Clop\nton, Miss Julia Tutwiler, Miss Zitella\nCocke, Miss Mary Johnston, MisS Howard\nWeeden, Miss Helen Keller. Miss Martha\nYoung, Mrs. R. D. Johnston and Miss\nNlmmo Greene.\nAnd the foregoing is but a partial and\nImperfect list.\nThe Other View\nFrom the St. Louis Republic.\n\"But, confound it all. you autoists cer\ntainly believe that pedestrians should\nstick to their rights, don\u2019t you?\u201d\n\u201cSure. But, dad blame it all, what can\nwe do when most of \u2019em keeps dodg\ning to their lefts.\u201d\nOSCAR W. UNDERWOOD\n\u2014Photo by Stephenson\nAmong the many men in public life v hose achievements have reflected last\ning credit upon the state of Alabama, none stands higher than Oscar W. Under\nwood of Birmingham, representative in congress from this district, and leader\nof the democratic majority on the floor of the House of Representatives.\nNo one more than Mr. Underwood has taken a more prominent part in shap\ning the policies of the nation since Congress became democratic five years\nsince. When the present president, Woodrow Wilson, was still president in\nPrinceton Mr. Underwood was going forward with his work In favor of tariff\nand currency reform and it is acknowledged by the president, himself, that Mr.\nUnderwood\u2019s splendid leadership of the Lower House has been of the utmost as\nsistance in the success of the party and its policies. Indeed, there is no one in\nthe country among his enemies who is not willing to admit that Oscar Under\nwood\u2019s public 1 if\u00bb* has been characterized constantly by a calm, consistent states\nmanship of unblemished integrity and great ability. Since he lias been\nleader of the Lower House In Congress Mr. Underwood has pressed forward the\ndemocratic policies to fruition as no other man has /leen able to do In many\nyears and he has won the reputation of always succeeding when he started out\nto put a measure through.\nIndeed, in many respects, Underwood was the most popular of all the candi\ndates for the presidential nomination at the Baltimore convention. When de\nfeated through a peculiar train of circumstances his friends still stood to him\nsteadfastly and loyally he told them with characteristic spirit that lie expected\nthem to show the same unswerving devotion to the cause us championed by Mr.\nWilson as though ho had, himself, been made their party's standard bearer. IBs\nown forceful and unstinted aid was one of the greatest assets of the Wilson cam\npaign and the president himself acknowledges that with Underwood as head of\nthe party in the house of representatives he is Yipheld by one of the greatest\nparty leaders in tin* country\u2019s history.\nHe is still a comparatively young man and his political fortunes arc gener\nally admitted to be so surely on the rise that he Is almost certain to be his\nparty\u2019s candidate for the presidency in 1916.\nWith characteristic modesty. Mr. Underwood has made his autobiography tn\nthe famous congressional directory the most brief of all that catalogue of public\nmen, but his fame is so gen. rally known throughout the country that hardly\nmore than a skeleton of Ids life facts are required.\nMr. Underwood, although a resident of Alabama for many years, is not a\nnative son of this state, having been born In Jefferson county, Ky., in Hie city\nof Louisville, on May 6, 1862.\nHe received his first education at the noted Rugby school In Louisville and\ncompleted his studies at the University of Virglna. Men who have known Mr.\nUnderwood since Ills school days will tell you that the high place In I i f he has\nwon is just what was to have been expected from his early ability, even tempera\nment and consistent work. He whs elected to tin* Fifty-fourth Congress first\nand lie has been re-elected by majorities of constantly increasing size to the\nFifty-fifth. Fifty-sixth, Fifty-seventh. Fifty-eighth, Fifty-ninth, Sixtieth, Sixty\nfirst and Sixty-second.\nLong before* the democrats worn their present supremacy in, the Lower\nHouse of the National Legislature. Mr. Fnderwood was leading them in minority\nwith the same rare skill and cairn porsistone.v which is now having' so much to\ndo with shaping the history of the nation, it is said of him that he Is the best\nloved man in the Lower House and none are quicker to admit his greatness than\nthe republicans whom he has opposed so long and so successfully.\nCAPTAIN REUBEN F. KOLB boasts that he first saw the light of clay\nin the governor producing county of Barbour. The great county of\nthe southeast, known in political parlance as the third grand divi\nsion of Alabama\u2014the other division being north Alabama and south\nAlabama\u2014has given the state three chief executives, and in Captain Kolb,\nthe only man who was twice elected governor, and on eacli occasion counted\nout. At one time, Captain Kolb was the oldest native born resident of\nEufaula.\nThere is no man in Alabama better known than Captain Kolb. The\ngreat majority of people know him intimately. The others know him by\nsight. Tiiose who have not seen the man, have heard of him. He has\nbeen active in Alabama politics and\nother affairs of Alabama\u2019s history\nfor a period preceding the war.\nCaptain Kolb was a soldier of the\nconfederacy. If is said (hat. he was\na brave man on the field of carnage,\nand one of the sternest disciplinar\nians in the service. He was known\nas \"Fighting Reuben.\" and it is said\nthat his personal courage in the\nheat, of battle was inspiring for his\nmen.\nFollowing tlie war, Captain Kolb\nreturned 10 Alabama and played\nhis part in redeeming the state from\nthe rule of the carpetbagger and the\nscalawag i he former overflowing\nthe st^ie in its helplessness, and the\nlatter springing up among their own\npeople for the purpose of profiting\nfrom the spoils of office.\nIn the '90 s Captain Kolb reached\nthe conclusion that the cdmmon\npeople of Alabama were not sharing\nIn the general return of prosperity,\nthat in other words by the aristo\ncratic element they were being\ngrossly discriminated against. He\ntold the people what he thought and\nwhat he believed, and he moved\n:hem as if by magic. They sprang\nup in a night, as It were, and pre\npared for one of the fiercest series\nof campaigns in the political his\ntory of the state. The \"white man's\nparty,\" as they called the organiza\ntion into which they welded them\nselves, stood like a rock. Every\nfarmer was a member. Every man\nof the hills was a member. As a\nmatter of fact, if the veterans of\nthose campaigns were to relate the\nBtory, they would declare that there\nwere very few people who were not\nmembers of the \"populistic\u201d brigade.\nThe day of the election rolled around. It Is now generally agreed\nthat Captain Kolb swept the state from top to bottom, from that sec\ntion through which sweeps the Tennessee, to the sun kissed shores of\nold Mobile. But Captain Kolb was not declared the winner. As a mat\nter of fae- it was announced that he had encountered defeat. In the light\nof the present, however, there Is scarcely a doubt but that he was counted\nout. And the following campaign he was again a candidate. Aguln he\nswept the state. Again he was denied the right to hold the office.\nFor a long while following these events Captain Kolb remained In\nactive. The demoeratie party was reorganised and those who had split\nCAPTAIS HBIBF.X F. KOLB\nand become known as \"populists'\u2019 were invited (o come again into the fold.\nConcessions were made by both sides. Tho quarrels were forgotten.\nThere was again a nulled democracy. At the present time, there is no\nanimosity. 'The people smile now over ilie Incidents of the campaigns of\n20 years ago which then were considered serious enough to cause neigh\nbor to draw his gnu against his neighbor in murder bent.\nIn the last campaign in the political history of the state. Capain Kolb\nasked the people to elect him to tho office of commissioner of agriculture.\nHe easily achieved the victory. He lias served well. His department is\nIn excellent condition, and liis work in Alabama has attracted compli\nmentary attention from llio outside. On farms and crops and cattle and\nhull weevils and cow ticks and kin\ndred subjects, there is no man in\nAlabama better Informed than Cap\ntain Kolb.\nAnd now he is asking again for\nthe office of governor, to which cm\ntwo other occasions, it is generally\nadmitted, he was elected. He is\nprepaying to make a vigorous cam\npaign, and there is every reason for\nhis friends to hope and believe that\nhe will bo in iho running all the way.\nand at the end, the victor. There\nitri been apparent a desire on the\nsurface that the \"wrongs of other\ndays be righted.\" Captain Kolb\nstates trial his old following is still\nwith him, and that the sons of the\nold fathers are now enlisted in the\nranks of his army.\nCaptain Kolb stands for peace\nafter turmoil, and prosperity after\ndepression caused by sol fish and un\nnecessary political agitation. He\nbelieves that the railroads should lie\nsupervised and regulated in regard\nto tiieir rates, hut not annihilated.\nHe believes that each county of the\nstate should have the right to ex\npress itself in regard to the liquor\ntraffic. He believes that Alabam\nians should invite capital to enter\nthe state and invest itself. He be\nlieves that there should be good\nroads in Ah bama, and tHat th<> con\nvicts should lie taken out of the\nmines, as soon as practical or ex\npedient. and put to work on the\nhighways. He believes that the\ngreat undeveloped water power of\nthe state should be harnessed and\nput to work earning dollars for the\npeople. He believes that the farm\nera should diversify their crops, and should be encouraged by the admin\nistrators of the stato\u2019B government. He believes that education should be\nplaced within the reach of every child In Alabama. He believes that the\nson of the rich should be educated, and that the barefoot boy and freckled\nTace girl of tho poor should be tutored and made able to cope with the\nmore fortunate.\nHis platform Is bused on snfe and Bane ldraa and Issues. He is not at\ntempting to excite the peoplo. He Is telling them that a long period of rest\nfrom polltloal turmoil la all that Is necessary to make Alabama the great\nest and richest and happiest of all the states of the union.","height":"27916","width":"19676"}}
